        <sect2 xml:id="ADJ_ADV_notes">
            <title>Notes</title>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para> No distinction is made between singular and plural adjectives in the
                        positive degree. </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para> In the comparative and superlative degrees, no distinctions are made with
                        respect to the case or number of adjectives. </para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </sect2>
        <sect2 xml:id="colors">
            <title>Colors</title>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para> The basic tag for basic color terms is ADJ. </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para> If a color term is also a substantive noun (e.g.,
                            <emphasis>orange</emphasis> in English), then it may be tagged
                            <emphasis>either</emphasis> ADJ <emphasis>or</emphasis> N depending on
                        the syntactic context. </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para> Color terms that neither modify a noun nor function as the predicate of a
                        clause are tagged N. For example, in English: <itemizedlist>
                            <listitem>
                                <para> the white/N of an egg </para>
                            </listitem>
                            <listitem>
                                <para> a black/N like that of jet </para>
                                <para> a deep red/N </para>
                            </listitem>
                        </itemizedlist>
                    </para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </sect2>
        <sect2 xml:id="degree_words">
            <title>Degree Words</title>
            <para> Degree words (e.g., οὕτως, ἱκανός) are treated as comparatives. See <xref
                    linkend="ἱκανός"/> for details. </para>
        </sect2>
        <sect2 xml:id="ordinal_numbers">
            <title>Ordinal Numbers</title>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para> Ordinal numbers are tagged ADJ. </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para> πρῶτος also has an adverbial use. See <xref linkend="πρῶτος"/> for
                        details. </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para> Cases where an ordinal might be expected but without overt ordinal
                        marking are treated as cardinal numbers (NUM).
                        <!-- Not sure if this applies in Greek. -->
                    </para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </sect2>
    </sect1>
